{"cursor":"3393","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"Ths is a 'list of recoilless rifles' (RCL) intended to catalogue these\nlightweight infantry support weapons that allow the firing of a heavier\nprojectile than would be practical with a recoiling artillery guns. Technically,\nonly devices that use a rifled barrel are recoilless rifles. The smoothbore\nvariants (those devoid of rifling) are termed recoilless guns. This distinction\nis often lost, and both are often called recoilless rifles.\n\nNormally used for anti-tank roles, the first effective system of this kind was\ndeveloped during World War II to provide infantry with light, cheap and easily\ndeployable weapon that does not require extensive training in gunnery. The near\ncomplete lack of recoil allows some versions to be shoulder-fired, but the\nmajority are mounted on light tripods and are intended to be easily carried by a\nsoldier. Carl Gustav m/42\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:98%;\"\n|-\n! width=12% | Caliber (mm) width=47% | Weapon name width=24% | Country of origin\n! width=19% | Period\n|- 20 mm Carl Gustav m/42\n|\n| World War II - 30 mm Rheinmetall RMK30\n|\n| modern - 50 mm Jagdfaust\n|\n| World War II - 57 mm M18 Kromuskit\n|\n| World War II / Cold War - 73 mm SPG-9\n|\n| Cold War /Modern - 74 mm Miniman\n|\n| Cold War - 75 mm LG 40\n|\n| World War II - 75 mm M20\n|\n| World War II / Cold War - 80 mm Breda Folgore\n|\n| Cold War / Modern - 82 mm BzK vzor 59\n|\n| Cold War - 82 mm B-10\n|\n| Cold War - 82 mm M-60\n|\n| Cold War - 84 mm M3 Carl Gustav\n|\n| Cold War /Modern - 84 mm AT4\n|\n| Modern - 88 mm 55 S 55\n|\n| Cold War - 88 mm RCL 3.45 inch Gun\n|\n| World War II - 90 mm Pvpj 1110\n|\n| Cold War / Modern - 90 mm M67\n|\n| Cold War - 94 mm RCL 3.7 inch Gun\n|\n| World War II / Cold War - 95 mm 95 S 58-61\n|\n| Cold War - 105 mm LG 40\n|\n| World War II - 105 mm LG 42\n|\n| World War II - 105 mm LG 43\n|\n| World War II - 105 mm Modelo 1968\n|\n| Col